</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:9pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">1 </SUP>For Mr.&nbsp;Stiehl, his 2018 long-term incentive awards were
granted before his promotion to Chief Financial Officer, and his target award value was therefore based on his rate of base salary and target percentage as then in effect. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><U>2018-2020 PSU Awards (Weighted 70%)</U>. PSU awards provide for three-year performance periods with a targeted number of shares to be earned if
performance during the period meets goals set during the first 90 days of the period. During the first quarter of 2018, the Compensation Committee established PSU award target levels for the performance period starting January&nbsp;1, 2018 for the
named executive officers. We refer to these as the 2018-2020 PSUs. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">If performance is below defined threshold levels, then no units will be earned,
and if performance exceeds defined maximum levels, then a maximum number of units (above the target number) will be earned and settled by issuance of shares (one share per unit earned). In this manner, PSUs are intended to align named executive
officer compensation closely to our performance while giving the named executive officers the opportunity for exceptional value if performance targets are exceeded. The vesting conditions for the PSUs also encourage the retention of our named
executive officers. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The 70% portion of the long-term incentive award dollar amount assigned to the PSUs was separately allocated to each of the
weighted performance metrics for the award, as follows: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="92%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">

dollar amount by the accounting value per share for that portion of the award (based on the Monte Carlo simulation value as of the grant date). Similarly, the target number of PSUs for the consolidated adjusted EBITDA margin and net sales CAGR
portions were determined by dividing the allocated portion of the target dollar amount by the closing price of our common stock on the grant date. In each case, the target number of PSUs was rounded up to the next whole unit. </P>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">46 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The Compensation Committee selected relative TSR as a metric to balance achievement of internal goals
with performance against our peers in an easily measurable metric that directly demonstrates value creation for our stockholders. The Compensation Committee recognized that the consolidated adjusted EBITDA margin metric provides further alignment
with the broader Annual Incentive Plan and our goal to improve quality of earnings. The Compensation Committee also recognized that net sales CAGR is a measure of additional alignment with our top line growth. The results of each metric will
determine the number of shares earned for that metric, based on that metric&#146;s weighting. The total award will be the addition of the total number of shares earned for each of the three performance metrics. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">TSR represents the percent change in the share price from the beginning of the performance period to the end of the performance period and assumes
immediate reinvestment of dividends when declared at the closing share price on the date declared. The beginning share price will be calculated as an average of 31 data points: the closing share price on January&nbsp;2, 2018 and the closing share
price <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">+/-15</FONT> trading days from January&nbsp;2, 2018. The ending share price will be calculated as an average of 31 data points: the closing share price on December&nbsp;31, 2020 and the closing share price <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">+/-15</FONT> trading days from December&nbsp;31, 2020. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The performance of this metric will be assessed in comparison of
the percentile rank to the approved peer group of companies. The lowest ranked company will be the 0% rank, the middle ranked company will be the 50th percentile rank and the top ranked company will be the 100th percentile rank. If a company is
acquired or otherwise is no longer publicly traded and its share price is no longer available, it will be excluded from the peer group. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The
three-year relative TSR percentile rank at threshold, target and maximum for the performance period follows: </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>2018-2020 PSUs </B></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>RELATIVE TSR PERFORMANCE GOAL </B></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><B>(weighted 34%)
</B></P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" ALIGN="center">


<TR>
<TD WIDTH="28%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="9%"></TD>
<TD WIDTH="25%"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="9%"></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" WIDTH="10%"></TD></TR>
<TR BGCOLOR="#12737c" STYLE="page-break-inside:avoid ; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:7pt">
<TD VALIGN="middle" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Achievement</FONT></B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">TSR Percentile Rank</FONT></B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" COLSPAN="2" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">%&nbsp;of&nbsp;Target&nbsp;Earned</FONT></B></FONT></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD></TR>


<TR STYLE="font-size:1pt">
<TD HEIGHT="2"></TD>

STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pro-rata</FONT> calculation of the number of shares earned, except that no shares for this metric will be earned for three-year relative TSR percentile rank below the 25th percentile. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The consolidated adjusted EBITDA margin metric measures 2020 consolidated adjusted EBITDA as a percentage of 2020 net sales, subject to certain
adjustments. For this purpose, (1)&nbsp;&#147;2020 consolidated adjusted EBITDA&#148; is our earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization for calendar year 2020, derived from our U.S. GAAP net earnings, subject to certain specified
adjustments and (2)&nbsp;&#147;2020 net sales&#148; is our &#147;net sales&#148; for 2020 as reported in our Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for 2020, subject to certain specified adjustments. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right">47 </P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The net sales CAGR metric measures the CAGR for net sales for the performance period against the baseline of 2017 net sales. The CAGR will be determined
using the standard CAGR formula and based on 2020 net sales. For this purpose, &#147;net sales&#148; for 2017 and 2020 means our net sales for 2017 and 2020, as applicable, as reported in our Annual Report on Form
<FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for the applicable year and, for 2020 Net Sales, measured&nbsp;at the 2018 budgeted foreign exchange rates. </P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><U>2018 RSA Awards (Weighted 30%)</U>. RSA awards vest in equal annual installments over the three-year period following the date of grant in February
2018. The named executive officer must remain employed with us through each vesting date to earn the shares vesting on that date, other than in case of termination of employment for death or disability, or an involuntary termination within two years
after a change in control. In this manner, RSAs encourage retention of our named executive officers, while also aligning their interests with those of our long-term stockholders. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The number of RSAs was determined by dividing the 30% portion of the long-term incentive award dollar amount assigned to the RSAs by the closing price
of our common stock on the grant date (rounded up to the next whole share). </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">48 </P>

<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">1</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7.5pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="justify">Adjusted EBITDA margin metric measured 2018 consolidated adjusted EBITDA as a percentage of 2018 net sales, subject
to certain exclusions. For this purpose, (a) &#147;2018 consolidated adjusted EBITDA&#148; is our earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization for calendar year 2018, derived from our U.S. GAAP net earnings, adjusted to exclude
certain specified items and (b) &#147;2018 net sales&#148; is our net sales for 2018 as reported in our Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for 2018. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:7.5pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">2</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7.5pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="justify">The TSR metric measures the percent change in share price from the beginning of the performance period to the end of
the performance period and assumes immediate reinvestment of dividends when declared at the closing share price on the date declared. The beginning share price was calculated as an average of 31 data points: the closing share price on
January&nbsp;4, 2016 and the closing share price +/- 15 trading days from January&nbsp;4, 2016. The ending share price was calculated as an average of 31 data points: the closing share price on December&nbsp;31, 2018 and the closing share price +/-
15 trading days from December&nbsp;31, 2018. The performance of this metric was assessed in comparison of the percentile rank to the approved peer group of companies. The lowest ranked company was the 0 percentile rank, the middle ranked company was
the 50th percentile rank and the top ranked company was the 100th percentile rank. If a company was acquired or otherwise is no longer publicly traded and its share price no longer available, it was excluded from the peer group.
</P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><B><I>Governance of Our Executive Compensation Program </I></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I>Oversight by the Compensation Committee </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The Compensation Committee is responsible for establishing and implementing our executive compensation philosophy and for ensuring that the total
compensation paid to our named executive officers and other executives is fair and competitive and motivates high performance. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Under our executive
compensation philosophy, we provide compensation in the forms and at levels that will permit us to retain and motivate our existing executives and to attract new executives with the skills and attributes that we need. The compensation program is
intended to provide appropriate and balanced incentives toward achieving our annual and long-term strategic objectives, to support a performance-oriented environment based on the attainment of goals and objectives intended to benefit our Company and
our stockholders, and to create an alignment of interests between our executives and our stockholders. The compensation program is designed to place a greater weight on rewarding the achievement of our longer-term objectives and financial
performance. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I>Role of Independent Compensation Consultant </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">FW Cook advises the Compensation Committee on the selection of peer companies, provided comparative industry trends and peer group data regarding
salary, annual incentive and long-term </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right">49 </P>

</DIV></Center>

<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">
incentive compensation levels for our executive officers and other key executives, and advised on recommended compensation levels for our management. FW Cook assisted the Compensation Committee
in selecting metrics and goals for the 2018 annual bonus program and the 2018-2020 PSUs. The Compensation Committee has assessed the independence of FW Cook pursuant to SEC rules and concluded that no conflict of interest exists that would prevent
FW Cook from serving as an independent consultant to the Compensation Committee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I>Role of CEO and Management </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The Compensation Committee from time to time directs members of management to work with FW Cook to provide executive compensation information or
recommendations to the Compensation Committee. However, the Compensation Committee has not delegated any of its authority to determine executive compensation programs, practices or other decisions to our management. As noted above, the current
executive compensation program was developed and approved by the Compensation Committee with advice and support from FW Cook after consulting with the CEO and our compensation and legal professionals. The CEO and other executive officers and
compensation professionals attend portions of meetings as requested by the Compensation Committee. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">While the Compensation Committee approved
metrics for the 2018 annual bonus and long-term incentive programs, FW Cook, the CEO and other members of our management also were consulted in developing the metrics and establishing the goals for the 2018 programs. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The CEO submits salary and bonus recommendations to the Compensation Committee for the other named executive officers as well as for the other
executives whose compensation is set by the Compensation Committee. In addition, the Compensation Committee has delegated to the CEO limited authority to make equity awards to employees who are not executive officers. The CEO does not provide input
regarding his own compensation and does not participate in any related Compensation Committee deliberations. Following a review of those recommendations with FW Cook, the Compensation Committee approves compensation decisions for our named executive
officers. In making compensation decisions for named executive officers other than the CEO, the Compensation Committee relies on the CEO&#146;s recommendations but makes independent adjustments and is not bound by those recommendations. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I>Use of Peer Group Data </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The
Compensation Committee uses data from a peer group as a factor in setting executive compensation levels and in designing executive compensation programs. The peer group is reviewed annually by the Compensation Committee. The Compensation Committee
includes companies primarily in the materials sector that are comparable to Sealed Air based on sales, percentage of sales outside of the United States, number of employees and market capitalization. The table below sets forth the peer group of
companies that the Compensation Committee considers in setting executive compensation levels and in designing compensation programs. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:12pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The Compensation Committee considers comparative executive compensation levels and practices based on
information from the peer companies as well as other data provided by FW Cook related to general industry executive compensation trends. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><B><I>Other Features and Policies </I></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT
 COLOR="#12737c"><I>Stock Ownership Guidelines </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">In order to align the interests of named executive officers and stockholders, we believe
that our named executive officers should have a significant financial stake in Sealed Air. To further that goal, we have stock ownership guidelines that apply to our named executive officers and other key executives. The guidelines for our named
executive officers are as follows: </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Executive officers are required to hold a multiple of their salary: 6 for the CEO, 3.5 for the CFO; 3 for the other
Senior Vice Presidents; and 2 for all other executive officers; </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Share equivalents held in our <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> retirement plans are included, but
unvested awards under our equity compensation plans are excluded; </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Until the minimum stock ownership has been reached, executive officers are expected to retain all shares received as
awards under our equity compensation programs after payment of applicable taxes; and </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">The Compensation Committee can approve exceptions to the stock ownership guidelines for executive officers in the event
of financial hardship. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">As of March&nbsp;18, 2019, all of our named executive officers had met the ownership guidelines or had
shares retained at vesting as required by the guidelines. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I>Savings, Retirement and Health and Welfare Benefits </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Our named executive officers participate in the retirement programs available generally to employees in the countries in which they work because we
believe that participation in these programs and in the other health and welfare programs mentioned below is an important part of a competitive compensation package. In the United States, our named executive officers participate in a <FONT
STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> defined contribution retirement plan, the Sealed Air Corporation 401(k) and Profit-Sharing Plan. As a result of participating in this broad-based retirement plan, our executive officers are eligible to
receive profit-sharing and matching contributions paid by us, up to IRS limits applicable to <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> plans. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Mr.&nbsp;Deily also participates in the Sealed Air Corporation Restoration Plan for Cryovac Employees, a component plan of the Sealed Air Combined
Pension Plan and a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> defined benefit plan that covers the employees of our Cryovac operations who participated in a defined benefit plan maintained by a previous employer immediately prior to
March&nbsp;31, 1998. The Restoration Plan for Cryovac Employees is described under &#147;&#151;Pension Benefits in 2018&#148; below. The plan was amended to freeze benefit accruals as of December&nbsp;31, 2016, and as a result, no additional
benefits will be accrued under the plan after 2016. Mr.&nbsp;Deily currently does not have any cumulative benefit under that plan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">U.S.-based named
executive officers may elect to defer a portion of salary or cash incentive awards under our nonqualified deferred compensation plan. The Compensation Committee believes that this plan is appropriate because executives are limited in the amount that
they can save for retirement under the 401(k) and Profit-Sharing Plan due to IRS limits applicable to <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">tax-qualified</FONT> retirement plans. No employer contributions are provided under the deferred compensation
plan. For 2018, Mr.&nbsp;Stiehl, Mr.&nbsp;Chrisman and Mr.&nbsp;Deily each elected to participate in the plan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">We do not offer any other
nonqualified excess or supplemental benefit plans to our named executive officers in the United States. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right">51 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">All of our named executive officers participate in the health, life insurance, disability benefits and
other welfare programs that are provided generally to employees in the countries in which they work. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I>Perquisites and Other Personal
Benefits </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Consistent with our performance-oriented environment, we provided limited perquisites to our named executive officers, as
included under the &#147;All Other Compensation&#148; column in &#147;&#151;2018 Summary Compensation Table.&#148; The limited perquisites we do provide are intended to provide a competitive compensation package for retention and recruitment. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I>Compensation Recoupment (Clawback) Policy </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Our compensation recoupment (clawback) policy, or the Recoupment Policy requires each executive officer to reimburse us for all or a portion of any
annual or long-term incentive compensation paid to the executive officer based on achievement of financial results that were subsequently the subject of a restatement due to error or misconduct regardless of whether the executive officer was
responsible for the error or misconduct so long as no payment or award or a lower payment or award would have been made to the officer based on the restated results. The Board of Directors will make the determination whether to seek recovery. The
Recoupment Policy is part of our overall risk management practices to ensure that compensation programs do not encourage manipulation of financial results. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">In addition, the Recoupment Policy provides that our CEO and CFO must reimburse us for any compensation or profits from the sale of securities under
Section&nbsp;304 of the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002. The Recoupment Policy has been incorporated into our equity award documents. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I>Employment, Severance and Change in Control Arrangements </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><U>Employment Agreements</U>. We do not generally enter into employment agreements with executive officers or other employees except in countries
outside the United States where such agreements are customary or as necessary for recruitment. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">We entered into an offer letter agreement with
Mr.&nbsp;Doheny, dated September&nbsp;5, 2017, in connection with his recruitment. We received guidance from FW Cook in the negotiation of the offer letter agreement. The offer letter agreement includes provisions regarding Mr.&nbsp;Doheny&#146;s
position and duties, compensation, post-employment covenants and other matters, including provisions regarding certain <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">new-hire</FONT> equity awards described above and certain severance benefits described under
&#147;&#151;Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control&#148; below. The Compensation Committee believes that the terms of the offer letter agreement are reasonable and were necessary to cause him to accept a significant leadership role with
Sealed Air. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><U>Executive Severance Plan</U>. In early 2014, the Compensation Committee established the Executive Severance Plan. This plan provides
for reasonable severance benefits in the case of an executive&#146;s involuntary termination of employment, either by us without &#147;cause&#148; or by the executive for &#147;good reason.&#148; The Compensation Committee believes that the
Executive Severance Plan serves the interests of stockholders by encouraging the retention of a stable management team. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Under the Executive
Severance Plan, in the case of an involuntary termination of employment without cause or with good reason, the executive is eligible for severance benefits in the form of continuation of base salary and health and welfare benefits for a period of
months (ranging from 3 to 12 months) based on the employee&#146;s years of service with us. In February 2018, the Compensation Committee approved an amendment to the Executive Severance Plan to (a)&nbsp;fix the severance period at 12 months
regardless of years of service and (b)&nbsp;determine the cash severance on the sum of the covered executive&#146;s base salary and target annual bonus. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">52 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">If the qualifying termination occurs upon or within two years after a change in control of Sealed Air,
the executive is instead entitled to receive (1)&nbsp;a lump sum payment equal to two years of base salary (or after the February 2018 amendment, the sum of base salary and target annual bonus), (2)&nbsp;continued health and welfare benefits for up
to 18 months, and (3)&nbsp;accelerated vesting of all outstanding equity compensation awards. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Severance benefits are conditioned upon the executive
giving us a general release of claims at the time of separation. Benefits are also conditioned upon the executive&#146;s compliance with certain restrictive covenants regarding <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-disparagement,</FONT>
confidentiality and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> (in addition to any other restrictive covenants to which an employee may be subject). No tax <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-ups</FONT> are provided to any
participant under the plan in case of any excise taxes under Sections 280G and 4999 of the Internal Revenue Code as a result of payments under the plan in connection with a change in control. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">If an executive covered by the plan is also entitled to severance under an existing agreement with us, the terms of the individual severance agreement
will control instead of the plan. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><U>Confidentiality and Restrictive Covenants Agreement</U>. Exempt employees who are eligible to receive equity
awards are required to sign a Confidentiality and Restrictive Covenants Agreement which addresses confidentiality of our proprietary information and disclosure and assignment of inventions as well as an eighteen-month post-employment restrictive
covenants obligation as a condition of receiving an equity award. In recent years, most other exempt new employees in the United States have been required to enter into an appropriate Restrictive Covenant and Confidentiality Agreement with us. These
agreements address the confidentiality of our proprietary information and disclosure and assignment of inventions to us and include at least an eighteen-month post-employment restrictive covenant obligation by the employee. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I>Timing of Equity Grants </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">PSU
and RSA awards made to our executive officers under our equity compensation plans are made during the first 90 days of each year, either at the regularly-scheduled meeting of the Compensation Committee held in February of each year or at a special
meeting held later but during the first 90 days of the year. In addition, SLO awards are made effective on a date set by the Compensation Committee in advance but no later than March&nbsp;15 to those executive officers who have elected to receive a
portion of their annual incentive award as an SLO award. The date is selected based on when the Compensation Committee expects that all annual incentive awards will be determined and to allow our staff sufficient time to assist executive officers to
make required SEC filings for the SLO awards on a timely basis. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">To the extent that other awards of restricted stock or restricted stock units may
be made to executive officers, they are generally made at one of the regularly-scheduled meetings or by unanimous written consents of the Compensation Committee. Awards are generally effective on the date of such meeting or unanimous written
consent. Dates for Compensation Committee meetings are usually set during the prior year, and the timing of meetings and awards is unrelated to the release of material <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-public</FONT> information. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I>Section&nbsp;162(m) Considerations </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Internal Revenue Code Section&nbsp;162(m) limits the deductibility of compensation in excess of $1&nbsp;million paid to any one named executive officer
in any calendar year. Under the tax rules in effect before 2018, compensation that qualified as &#147;performance-based&#148; under Section&nbsp;162(m) was deductible without regard to this $1&nbsp;million limit. In 2017 and prior years, the
Compensation Committee designed awards under the Annual Incentive Plan and our Performance-Based Compensation Program, as well as PSUs under equity incentive plans, that were intended to qualify for this performance-based compensation exception.
However, the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act, which was signed into law </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right">53 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">
December&nbsp;22, 2017, eliminated this performance-based compensation exception effective January&nbsp;1, 2018, subject to a special rule that &#147;grandfathers&#148; certain awards and
arrangements that were in effect on or before November&nbsp;2, 2017. As a result, compensation that the Compensation Committee structured in 2017 and prior years with the intent of qualifying as performance-based compensation under
Section&nbsp;162(m) that is paid on or after January&nbsp;1, 2018 may not be fully deductible, depending on the application of the special grandfather rules. Moreover, from and after January&nbsp;1, 2018, compensation awarded in excess of
$1&nbsp;million to our named executive officers generally will not be deductible. While the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act will limit the deductibility of compensation paid to the named executive officers, the Compensation Committee will&#151;consistent with
its past practice&#151;design compensation programs that are intended to be in the best long-term interests of Sealed Air and our stockholders, with deductibility of compensation being one of a variety of considerations taken into account. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I><A NAME="toc685314_27"></A>Compensation Committee Report </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:14pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The Organization and Compensation Committee has reviewed and discussed the Compensation Discussion and Analysis with management. Based on its review and
discussions with management, the members of the Committee recommended to the Board of Directors that the Compensation Discussion and Analysis be included in Sealed Air&#146;s 2019 Proxy Statement and incorporated by reference into Sealed Air&#146;s
Annual Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for the fiscal year ended December&nbsp;31, 2018. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Organization and Compensation
Committee </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Jacqueline B. Kosecoff, Chair </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Michael Chu </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Richard L. Wambold </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I><A NAME="toc685314_28"></A>Board Oversight of Compensation Risks </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">We believe that risks arising from our compensation policies and practices for our employees are not reasonably likely to have a material adverse effect
on Sealed Air. In 2018 as in prior years, at the request of the Compensation Committee and with the assistance of FW&nbsp;Cook, we evaluated our incentive compensation plans relative to our enterprise risks and determined that there were no
significant changes to the compensation risks identified below. We determined, taking into account advice from FW&nbsp;Cook, that there were no significant risk areas from a compensation risk perspective. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">With respect to our executive compensation programs, a number of risk mitigation features were in place in 2018, including the following: </P>
<P STYLE="font-size:10pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">The primary metric for the Annual Incentive Plan focused on earnings (consolidated adjusted EBITDA, profit to growth
ratio and ratio of working capital to net trade sales), and the Compensation Committee had discretion to adjust bonus pool funding and individual award payouts. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">The principal long-term incentive program for executives is PSU awards that vest based on achievement of measurable
financial three-year goals balanced by relative stock return performance. No stock options were used. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

otherwise earned. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

and manipulation of financial results. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">54 </P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>

<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>

<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt">Our stock ownership guidelines require executives to hold at least a portion of vested equity awards during employment,
thus discouraging excessive risk taking. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

on a single metric. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I><A NAME="toc685314_29"></A>2018 Summary Compensation Table </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The following table includes information as to 2018 compensation for our CEO, our CFO and our three other most highly compensated executive officers
during 2018 who served as such at the end of the year. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">1</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7.5pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="justify">The Stock Awards column shows the value of equity awards granted during the year indicated. The amounts do not
correspond to the actual amounts that may be earned by the named executive officers. Equity awards granted during each year may include: (a)&nbsp;awards of restricted stock, or RSAs, and restricted stock units, or RSUs, under the 2014 Incentive
Plan; (b)&nbsp;SLO awards under the Annual Incentive Plan; and (c)&nbsp;PSU awards granted under the 2014 Incentive Plan. RSA and RSU awards are valued at the grant date fair value computed in accordance with FASB ASC Topic 718. SLO awards are
valued at the fair value at the service inception date based on the percentage of the target bonus to be paid as an SLO award, increased by the 25% premium, using (for 2018) the average closing price of our common stock for the first 15 trading days
of the calendar year, where the service inception date is the beginning of the calendar year. PSU awards are valued based on the grant date fair value on the date on which the PSU award was granted by the Compensation Committee. In valuing the SLO
awards and PSU awards, we assumed the probable achievement of the target levels for the primary performance goals. Pursuant to SEC rules, the amounts shown exclude the impact of estimated forfeitures. For the portion of PSU awards earned based on
relative TSR, the grant date fair value is based on a Monte Carlo simulation that determines the likely payout of the award (which were $57.14 per share for the PSUs granted on February&nbsp;17, 2016; $46.07 per share for the PSU granted on
March&nbsp;21, 2017; and $43.40 per share for the PSU granted on February&nbsp;13, 2018). For the new hire PSUs awarded to Mr.&nbsp;Doheny on September&nbsp;18, 2017 in connection with his employment, the grant date fair value is $10.63 per share
based on a Monte Carlo simulation. For additional assumptions made in valuing these awards and other information, see Note 19, &#147;Stockholders&#146; Equity (Deficit),&#148; of Notes to our consolidated financial statements included in our Annual
Report on Form <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">10-K</FONT> for the fiscal year ended December&nbsp;31, 2018. For the PSU awards granted on February&nbsp;13, 2018, the value of the awards as of the grant date, assuming that the highest level of
performance conditions would be achieved (which is 200% of target for the 2018-2020 PSUs), is as follows: </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I><A NAME="toc685314_30"></A>Grants of Plan-Based Awards in 2018 </I></FONT></P>

 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">56 </P>

<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">

<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:7pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="justify">The threshold number of shares for 2018-2020 PSU awards is 25% of the target number of shares for the relative TSR
portion plus 50% of the target number of shares for the EBITDA margin and net sales CAGR portions, and the maximum number of shares for such awards is 200% of the target number of shares. Shares, to the extent earned, will be issued in 2021 for the
2018-2020 PSU awards. See &#147;&#151;Compensation Discussion and Analysis&#151;2018 Compensation Decisions: Base Salary and Incentive Compensation&#151;Long-Term Incentive Compensation.&#148; </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="font-size:2pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:7pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">4</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="justify">This column shows the fair value on the grant date or service inception date of the equity awards shown in the table
computed in accordance with FASB ASC Topic 718. The manner in which grant date fair value was determined for awards granted in 2018 is discussed in Note 1 under &#147;&#151;2018 Summary Compensation Table.&#148; The amounts shown exclude the impact
of estimated forfeitures. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I>Description of Annual and Long-Term Incentive Awards in the 2018 Summary Compensation Table
and the Grants of Plan-Based Awards in 2018 Table </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><I>Annual Incentive Plan: Cash Bonuses and SLO Awards</I>. Each of the named executive
officers has a target bonus that is established by the Compensation Committee during the first quarter of the year. Also, certain of the named executive officers have the opportunity at a time determined by the Compensation Committee (generally
prior to the start of the performance year) to designate a portion of his or her annual bonus to be received as a SLO award under the 2014 Incentive Plan. (Beginning in 2019, no new executive officers may make this election.) The portion to be
denominated as SLO awards, in increments of 25% of the annual bonus, may be given a premium to be determined by the Compensation Committee each year. The stock price used to calculate the number of shares that can be earned is the average closing
price for the first 15 trading days of the performance year, thereby reflecting stock price changes during the performance year in the value of the SLO award. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Once the amount of the annual bonus has been determined for each named executive officer following the end of the year, the cash portion is paid out
shortly thereafter, and the SLO award is provided in the form of an award of restricted stock units under the 2014 Incentive Plan that vest on the second anniversary of the grant date. The SLO restricted stock unit awards are granted on a date
determined by the Compensation Committee, but no later than March&nbsp;15 following the end of the performance year. For the &#147;principal portion&#148; of the award that would have otherwise been paid in cash, the award vests earlier upon any
termination of employment, other than for cause. For the &#147;premium portion&#148; of the award equal to the additional 25%, the award vests earlier only in case of death, disability or retirement. Retirement for the purpose of SLO awards and the
PSU awards described below means (i)&nbsp;for PSU awards granted before 2018 and SLO awards through 2018 performance year, termination of employment after five or more years of employment and with years of employment plus age equal to 70 or more,
and (ii)&nbsp;for PSU awards granted beginning in 2018 and SLO awards beginning 2019 performance year, termination of employment after at least age 55 with at least 10 years of employment, and in each case excluding termination for cause. Except as
described above, if the recipient ceases to be employed by us prior to vesting, then the award is forfeited, except for certain circumstances following a change in control. SLO awards in the form of restricted stock units have no voting rights until
shares are issued to them but do receive a cash payment in the amount of the dividends (without interest) on the shares they have earned at about the same time that shares are issued to them following the period of restriction. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><I>Performance Share Unit Awards</I>. PSU awards, which were awarded under the 2014 Incentive Plan, generally provide for a three-year performance
period with a targeted number of shares to be earned if performance during the period meets goals set by the Compensation Committee during the first 90 days of the period. If performance is below defined threshold levels, then no units will be
earned, and if performance exceeds defined maximum levels, then a maximum number of units (above the target number) will be earned. PSU awards are not transferable by the participant until the end of the performance period and certification by the
Compensation Committee with respect to each performance measure used for the award. If a participant terminates employment during the performance period due to death, disability or retirement, then the participant (or his or her estate) will receive
a pro rata payout following the end of the performance period based on the portion of the performance period during which the participant was employed and based on the number of units that would have been earned by the participant if he or she had
remained employed for the entire performance period. If the participant leaves employment during the performance period for any other </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right">57 </P>

</DIV></Center>

 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">
reason, then the units are forfeited, except for certain circumstances following a change in control. At about the same time that shares are issued to participants following the performance
period, participants also receive a cash payment in the amount of the dividends (without interest) that would have been paid during the performance period on the number of shares that they have earned. Holders of PSU awards have no voting rights as
stockholders until shares of common stock are issued after the end of the performance period. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify"><I>Restricted Stock and Restricted Stock Units</I>.
Awards of restricted stock and restricted stock units included in &#147;&#151;2018 Summary Compensation Table&#148; were made under the 2014 Incentive Plan, which awards provide for a vesting period. For restricted stock awards granted as part of
the 2018 long-term incentive award, the award vests in equal installments annually over three years. Awards vest earlier in the event of the participant&#146;s death or disability. If a participant terminates employment prior to vesting, then the
award of restricted stock or restricted stock units is forfeited, except for certain circumstances following a change in control. Within 90 days following the date of termination, the Compensation Committee can waive the forfeiture of all or a
portion of an award. During the vesting period, holders of unvested shares of restricted stock are entitled to vote the unvested shares, while holders of restricted stock units have no voting rights. We do not pay dividends on unvested restricted
stock or restricted stock units. Instead following vesting, holders receive a cash payment in the amount of dividends (without interest) that would have been paid during the vesting period. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I><A NAME="toc685314_31"></A>Outstanding Equity Awards at 2018 Fiscal <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">Year-End</FONT> </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The following table shows, as of December&nbsp;31, 2018, outstanding and unvested stock awards under the 2014 Incentive Plan for the named executive
officers. All market or payout values in the table shown for stock awards are based on the closing price of common stock on December&nbsp;31, 2018 of $34.84 per share. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:10pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

stock units that vest on March&nbsp;14, 2020, or earlier (a)&nbsp;upon termination of employment, other than for cause, with respect to the &#147;principal portion&#148; or (b)&nbsp;in case of death, disability or retirement with respect to the
&#147;premium portion.&#148; As of December&nbsp;31, 2018, Mr.&nbsp;Deily is retirement eligible, and Mr.&nbsp;Chrisman is retirement eligible as to his 16SLO, 17SLO and 17PSU awards, but not as to his 18PSU award. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>

December&nbsp;31, 2019 that vest on the latter date. The amounts shown in this column for 17PSU awards represent 200% of the target number of shares based on performance through December&nbsp;31, 2018. 18PSU awards are performance share unit awards
for the performance period January&nbsp;1, 2018 through December&nbsp;31, 2020 that vest on the latter date. The amounts shown in this column for 18PSU awards represent 100% of the target number of shares based on performance through
December&nbsp;31, 2018. The PSUs are not settled until after the end of the performance period when performance results are certified by the Compensation Committee, usually at the regularly scheduled meeting in February, which generally approximates
three years after the original grant date. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>

 COLOR="#ffffff">Present&nbsp;Value&nbsp;of</FONT></B></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Accumulated</FONT></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">Benefit</FONT></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">($)</FONT></B></FONT></P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" COLSPAN="4" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-TOP:1px solid #000000; BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT

<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Last&nbsp;Fiscal&nbsp;Year&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</FONT></B></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:1pt; font-size:7pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="center"><FONT COLOR="#ffffff"><B><FONT COLOR="#ffffff">($)</FONT></B></FONT></P></TD></TR>

<TD VALIGN="middle" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:1.00em; text-indent:-1.00em; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">Mr.&nbsp;Deily</P></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" COLSPAN="4" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">Restoration&nbsp;Plan&nbsp;for&nbsp;Cryovac<BR>Employees</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000;">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000" ALIGN="right">34.0833</TD>
<TD NOWRAP VALIGN="middle" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000"></TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" COLSPAN="4" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">0</TD>
<TD VALIGN="bottom" STYLE=" BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</TD>
<TD VALIGN="middle" COLSPAN="4" ALIGN="center" STYLE="BORDER-BOTTOM:1px solid #000000">0</TD></TR>
<TR STYLE="font-size:1pt">
<TD HEIGHT="3.0"></TD>
<TD HEIGHT="3.0" COLSPAN="5"></TD>
<TD HEIGHT="3.0" COLSPAN="5"></TD>
<TD HEIGHT="3.0" COLSPAN="5"></TD>
<TD HEIGHT="3.0" COLSPAN="5"></TD></TR>
</TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The Restoration Plan for Cryovac Employees provides a retirement benefit that is based on the amount by which the
benefit assuming the participant had remained in the prior employer&#146;s defined benefit plan until retirement exceeds assumed profit-sharing benefits under our 401(k) and Profit-Sharing Plan plus the accrued benefit as of March&nbsp;31, 1998
under the prior employer&#146;s plan. This calculation resulted in an accumulated benefit for Mr.&nbsp;Deily of $0 at December&nbsp;31, 2018. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The
number of years of credited service at December&nbsp;31, 2018 includes service with the prior employer of 15.3 years for Mr.&nbsp;Deily. The present value of the accumulated benefit at December&nbsp;31, 2018 is calculated assuming a retirement age
of 65. The Restoration Plan for Cryovac Employees provides for normal retirement at age 65 and early retirement at age 55. Benefits are generally paid as a single life annuity, but benefits may be paid in other forms, including joint and survivor
annuities. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The normal retirement benefit is a monthly amount equal to the excess of (a)&nbsp;the sum of 1% of the average of the annual
compensation for the highest five consecutive <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">12-month</FONT> periods during the last 15 years of service (the final average compensation) plus 0.4 of 1% of the final average compensation in excess of the average
Social Security wage bases during the 35 years ending with the year in which the participant attains Social Security retirement age, multiplied by the years of credited service, over (b)&nbsp;the accrued monthly benefit as of March&nbsp;31, 1998
under the defined benefit plan maintained by the prior employer plus the participant&#146;s assumed accrued profit sharing benefit under our 401(k) and </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">60 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">
Profit-Sharing Plan. The early retirement benefit is calculated in a similar manner after applying actuarial equivalent factors to the calculation described in (a)&nbsp;of the preceding sentence
and based on the early retirement factors in effect on March&nbsp;31, 1998 under the defined benefit plan maintained by the prior employer. The participant&#146;s assumed accrued profit-sharing benefit under our 401(k) and Profit-Sharing Plan is
determined by crediting 10% annual interest prior to 2003 and 8.5% annual interest beginning in 2003 to our profit-sharing contributions to the 401(k) and Profit-Sharing Plan each year from the date of contribution to the date of determination,
summing all of these adjusted contributions, and converting the result to an annual benefit payable for the life of the participant. The Restoration Plan for Cryovac Employees also provides a <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">pre-retirement</FONT>
death benefit in the amount of 75% of the normal retirement benefit under a 75% joint and survivor annuity that would commence on the participant&#146;s 65th birthday. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">The Restoration Plan for Cryovac Employees was amended to freeze benefit accruals as of December&nbsp;31, 2016, and as a result, no additional benefits
will be accrued under the Restoration Plan for Cryovac Employees after 2016. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I><A NAME="toc685314_34"></A>Nonqualified Deferred Compensation
in 2018 </I></FONT></P> <P STYLE="margin-top:12pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Messrs. Stiehl, Chrisman and&nbsp;Deily participate in the Sealed Air Corporation Deferred Compensation Plan for Key Employees,
an unfunded nonqualified deferred compensation plan designed to provide selected employees the opportunity to defer the payment of a portion of base salary and certain cash annual incentive compensation. </P>

<P STYLE="font-size:3pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:8pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left"><SUP STYLE="font-size:85%; vertical-align:top">2</SUP>&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:8pt; font-family:ARIAL; " ALIGN="justify">This amount is not included in &#147;&#151;2018 Summary Compensation Table&#148; because earnings were not preferential
or above market. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Each year the Deferred Compensation Plan for Key Employees permits participating employees to elect to defer
(a)&nbsp;up to 50% of base salary for the year and (b)&nbsp;up to 100% of the cash annual incentive award for the year payable under our Annual Incentive Plan. Our Deferred Compensation Plan for Key Employees permits discretionary contributions by
us. Participant account balances are credited with interest as determined by the Compensation Committee, which has determined that accounts will be adjusted monthly based on the Moody&#146;s Seasoned Aaa Corporate Bond Yield for that month. </P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">A participant&#146;s account will be distributed based on the participant&#146;s payment election made at the time of deferral. A participant can elect
to have deferrals credited to a &#147;retirement account&#148; to be paid in a lump sum or installments (over 5, 10 or 15 years) commencing the seventh month after termination of employment or at a later age or date selected by the participant.
Alternatively, a participant can have up to two <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">&#147;in-service</FONT> accounts&#148; that will be payable in a lump sum or 5 annual installments on a date specified by the participant (or earlier upon a termination
of employment). </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right">61 </P>

</DIV></Center>


<p Style='page-break-before:always'>
<HR  SIZE="3" style="COLOR:#999999" WIDTH="100%" ALIGN="CENTER">
<h5 align="left"><a href="#toc">Table of Contents</a></h5>


<Center><DIV STYLE="width:8.5in" align="left">
 <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:12pt; font-family:ARIAL"><FONT COLOR="#12737c"><I><A NAME="toc685314_35"></A>Payments Upon Termination or Change in Control </I></FONT></P>
<P STYLE="margin-top:10pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">We do not have any severance programs or agreements covering any of our named executive officers, except for the arrangements described below and
benefits generally available to salaried employees, also noted below. We also have no programs or agreements providing any payments or benefits to our named executive officers in connection with a change in control, except as part of our equity
compensation awards and Executive Severance Plan as discussed in more detail below. The following describes arrangements that address cash payments or other benefits to certain of our named executive officers following termination of employment:
</P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt"><I>Doheny Offer Letter Agreement. </I>Mr.&nbsp;Doheny&#146;s offer letter agreement includes severance protection if
Mr.&nbsp;Doheny&#146;s employment is terminated by us without &#147;cause&#148; or by Mr.&nbsp;Doheny for &#147;good reason&#148; (as those terms are defined in the offer letter agreement). If the termination of employment occurs other than within
24 months after a change in control, the cash severance equals two times his annual salary and target annual bonus. If the termination of employment occurs on or within 24 months after a change in control, the cash severance equals three times the
sum of his salary and target annual bonus. Payments for a pro rata bonus and premiums for certain health benefits may also apply. The offer letter agreement does not provide for any tax <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-ups</FONT> for excise
taxes for payments in connection with a change in control, and instead provides for a &#147;best net&#148; cutback consistent with our standard practice for other senior executives. Payment of severance is conditioned on Mr.&nbsp;Doheny providing us
with a release of claims and complying with applicable covenants. Upon a termination without cause or with good reason on December&nbsp;31, 2018, Mr.&nbsp;Doheny would have received the amount of severance benefits shown in the table below.
</P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt"><I>Executive Severance Plan</I>: Our Executive Severance Plan provides severance benefits upon a qualifying termination
of employment to selected employees as designated by the Compensation Committee. Each of the named executive officers (other than Mr.&nbsp;Doheny) has been designated a participant in the Executive Severance Plan. Severance benefits are triggered
under the Executive Severance Plan upon a termination of employment (other than by reason of death or disability) by us without &#147;cause&#148; or by the employee for &#147;good reason&#148; (as those terms are defined in the Executive Severance
Plan). Severance benefits equal (a)&nbsp;one year of base salary and target annual bonus (payable over 12 months) and (b)&nbsp;continued health and welfare benefits for a period of 12 months. </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
<P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:6%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">If a termination without cause or for good reason occurs upon or within two years after a change in control, the employee is instead
entitled to receive (a)&nbsp;a lump sum payment equal to two years of the sum of base salary plus target annual bonus, (b)&nbsp;continued health and welfare benefits for up to 18 months, and (c)&nbsp;accelerated vesting of all outstanding equity
compensation awards. For this purpose, and consistent with the current provisions of our stockholder-approved 2014 Incentive Plan, accelerated vesting of any performance-based equity awards is based on assumed achievement of performance goals at the
greater of target performance or actual performance measured through the last quarter preceding the change in control. Additional details on treatment of equity awards upon termination of employment or following a change in control can be found
below. </P> <P STYLE="margin-top:6pt; margin-bottom:0pt; margin-left:6%; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="justify">Severance benefits are conditioned upon an employee giving us a general release of claims at the time of separation. Benefits
are also conditioned upon an employee&#146;s compliance with certain restrictive covenants regarding <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-disparagement,</FONT> confidentiality, and <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">non-competition</FONT> (in addition
to any other restrictive covenants to which an employee may be subject). No tax <FONT STYLE="white-space:nowrap">gross-ups</FONT> are provided to any participant under the Plan in case of any excise taxes under Sections 280G and 4999 of the Internal
Revenue Code as a result of payments under the Executive Severance Plan in connection with a change in control. If an employee covered by the Plan is also entitled to severance under an existing agreement with us, the terms of the individual
severance agreement will control instead of the Plan. </P>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL">62 </P>

</DIV></Center>

award becomes vested and payable or is forfeited upon termination of employment. The following briefly describes the key features of these provisions. See also &#147;&#151;Description of Annual and Long-Term Incentive Awards in the 2018 Summary
Compensation Table and the Grants of Plan-Based Awards in 2018 Table&#148; for more details. </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>

<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt"><I>Annual Bonus Awards: </I>Under our Annual Incentive Plan, employees must remain employed through the applicable
payment date in order to be entitled to receive an annual bonus for a year; otherwise, payment of the annual bonus is at our discretion. Bonuses are paid during the month of March for the prior year, so termination of the named executive officers as
of the end of 2018 would have meant that they were not entitled to receive a cash bonus or SLO award based on 2018 performance. For a termination of employment before the bonus payment date, the payment of an annual bonus is discretionary depending
on the circumstances. Under his offer letter agreement, however, Mr.&nbsp;Doheny will receive a pro rata annual bonus in case of a termination without cause or for good reason. The annual bonus paid (as cash and/or SLO award) under the Annual
Incentive Plan to each named executive officer for 2018 was as follows: Mr.&nbsp;Doheny, $1,495,540, Mr.&nbsp;Stiehl, $379,050; Mr.&nbsp;Chammas, $501,777; Mr.&nbsp;Chrisman, $349,276; and Mr.&nbsp;Deily, $497,364. These amounts may not represent
the amounts that would have been awarded if the named executive officers had terminated employment at the end of 2018 for any of the reasons noted above. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">
<TR style = "page-break-inside:avoid">
<TD WIDTH="4%">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top" ALIGN="left">&#149;</TD>
<TD WIDTH="1%" VALIGN="top">&nbsp;</TD>
<TD ALIGN="left" VALIGN="top"> <P ALIGN="justify" STYLE=" margin-top:0pt ; margin-bottom:0pt; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt"><I>Restricted Stock and Restricted Stock Units: </I>These awards will vest in full in case of death or disability before
the scheduled vesting date and will generally forfeit for any other termination of employment before the scheduled vesting date with five exceptions. First, SLO awards that have been awarded as RSUs after the end of the performance year will vest in
full upon retirement. Second, RSAs and RSUs will vest upon a termination of employment by us without cause or by the executive with good reason that occurs within two years after a change in control. Third, for SLO awards, the &#147;principal
portion&#148; that would have otherwise been paid in cash vests in full upon any termination other than a termination for cause. Fourth, Mr.&nbsp;Doheny&#146;s offer letter agreement provides for prorated vesting of his new hire RSUs (subject to
actual performance results for the performance-vesting RSUs) if he has been terminated without cause or terminates with good reason on or before December&nbsp;31, 2020. Fifth, within 90 days following the date of termination, the Compensation
Committee can waive the forfeiture of RSAs or RSUs. </P></TD></TR></TABLE> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:10pt" BORDER="0" CELLPADDING="0" CELLSPACING="0" WIDTH="100%">

the forfeiture of any outstanding PSU awards with two exceptions. First, in case of death, disability or retirement before the end of the performance period, a pro rata number </P></TD></TR></TABLE>
 <p STYLE="margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt ; font-size:8pt">&nbsp;</P> <P STYLE="margin-top:0pt; margin-bottom:0pt; font-size:10pt; font-family:ARIAL" ALIGN="right">63 </P>

of the PSUs will become payable after the end of the performance period, based on the actual performance results for the performance period. Second, in case of a change in control followed within
two years by a termination of employment without cause or by the executive with good reason (a &#147;qualifying termination&#148; for purposes of the table below), per the Executive Severance Plan, the PSUs will become payable as of the date of
termination based on target performance (or actual performance through the quarter prior to the change in control, if greater). </P></TD></TR></TABLE>

of employment as of December&nbsp;31, 2018, based on the closing price of our common stock of $34.84 as of December&nbsp;31, 2018. All awards remain subject to the Recoupment Policy (discussed in &#147;&#151;Compensation Discussion and
Analysis&#148; above). </P> <P STYLE="font-size:6pt;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt">&nbsp;</P>
<TABLE CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" WIDTH="100%" BORDER="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; font-family:ARIAL; font-size:7pt" ALIGN="center">
